In 2026, ChromaDB remains the most popular choice for "physical" local vector storage because it is simple, handles metadata beautifully, and requires almost zero configuration.
While FAISS is an in-memory library (a "Rolodex"), ChromaDB is a persistent database (a "Filing Cabinet").
1. The Key Difference in 2026
You should now use the partner package langchain-chroma instead of the older langchain-community version. It is faster and more stable for modern LLM workloads.
Installation:
pip install langchain-chroma chromadb

2. Implementation: Store and Retriever
This example shows how to create a "physical" database on your hard drive and then turn it into a Retriever for use in your AI chains.
from langchain_chroma import Chroma
from langchain_ollama import OllamaEmbeddings
from langchain_core.documents import Document

# 1. Setup local embeddings (Ollama)
embeddings = OllamaEmbeddings(model="nomic-embed-text")

# 2. Initialize Chroma with a "Physical" directory
# If this folder exists, Chroma will load it. If not, it will create it.
persist_dir = "./my_local_knowledge_base"

vector_store = Chroma(
    collection_name="tech_docs",
    embedding_function=embeddings,
    persist_directory=persist_dir
)

# 3. Add data (if the store is empty)
if vector_store.get()['ids'] == []:
    docs = [Document(page_content="ChromaDB is a persistent vector database.")]
    vector_store.add_documents(docs)
    print("Data saved to disk.")

# 4. CONVERT TO RETRIEVER
# This is the 'magic' step that connects to LangChain chains
retriever = vector_store.as_retriever(
    search_type="similarity",
    search_kwargs={"k": 2}
)

# 5. Use the retriever
results = retriever.invoke("What kind of database is Chroma?")
print(f"Found: {results[0].page_content}")

3. Why ChromaDB is the "Physical" King
| Feature | Why it wins for local dev |
|---|---|
| Auto-Persistence | Unlike FAISS, Chroma saves your data automatically as you add it. No save_local() needed. |
| Metadata Filtering | You can easily say: "Only search documents where category == 'Python'". |
| SQLite Backend | It uses a specialized SQLite engine, making it robust enough for small production apps. |
| Developer UI | You can run a separate Chroma server (chroma run) to inspect your data visually. |
4. Advanced: The "Multi-Vector" Retriever
Sometimes, a single text chunk is too small to have a good embedding. In 2026, we often use the Multi-Vector Retriever with Chroma. It stores a summary of a large document as the vector but returns the full document to the LLM.
> Wit's End: If FAISS is like keeping your contacts on a single sheet of paper in your pocket, ChromaDB is like having a full-blown address book with tabs, notes, and a leather cover. One is for speed; the other is for organization.
